  "metadata": {
    "title": "De novo sphingomyelin synthesis with regulation (Human) CerS5 Recon4IMD",
    "modelstate": "development",
    "deprecated": false,
    "date": "2025-10-28",
    "comment": "Normal CERT Function and Regulation:\nSphingolipids are crucial for membrane structure, signal transduction, and brain development and function, with their metabolism tightly regulated by homeostatic circuits.\nThe ceramide transporter (CERT) plays a central role in sphingolipid biosynthesis by transferring ceramide (Cer) from the endoplasmic reticulum (ER) to the trans-Golgi membrane, where it is converted to sphingomyelin (SM).\nUnder normal conditions, when sufficient rates of SM production are reached, CERT is phosphorylated and undergoes a conformational change that inactivates it, leading to its redistribution from membranes to the cytosol. This phosphorylation cycle involves protein kinase D (PKD) initiating phosphorylation at p.S132, followed by CSNK1G2 (casein kinase 1 γ 1) phosphorylating other sites in the serine-rich region (SRR), and the ER phosphatase PP2Cε reversing this action.",
